{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631655"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:30:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:30:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17387"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17387"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10077"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75490"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10077"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17387"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61000"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7722"},{"type":"tags","id":"7723"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23584"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23587"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75490"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher collects data about blood types among 200 hospital patients, recording the frequency of each ABO blood group (A, B, AB, and O).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate way to visualise this data?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bar chart","Scatter plot","Area chart","Line graph","Box and whisker plot"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebar chart\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate visualisation for this data because it effectively displays frequencies across distinct, non-overlapping categories (blood types). Bar charts are ideal for comparing quantities between different groups when the categories are nominal and discrete.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELine graph\u003C/strong\u003E - Line graphs are used to show trends over time or continuous data points with a meaningful connection between adjacent points. Blood types are categorical and not continuous.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScatter plot\u003C/strong\u003E - Scatter plots show relationships between two continuous variables. Blood type is a single categorical variable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBox and whisker plot\u003C/strong\u003E - Box plots display the distribution of continuous data, including median, quartiles, and outliers. They are not suitable for categorical frequencies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArea chart\u003C/strong\u003E - Area charts are similar to line graphs but with the area below the line filled in. They are used for continuous data over time, not categorical data.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBar charts provide clear visual comparison of frequencies or values across categories, with the height of each bar proportional to the frequency of each blood type.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bar charts are appropriate for comparing categorical data or discrete groups.","Bar charts should be used when displaying distinct, non-continuous categories with their corresponding frequencies or values.","Bar charts are ideal for showing comparisons between groups when the data is not time-based or continuous."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61000"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17387"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61000"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T21:19:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T00:54:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10077"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75490"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:53+